The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                            CRICKET BRIEFS
                                                    
	India climb to second spot  Calcutta: India climbed to second place in the LG ICC Test Championship table despite losing the four-match series with Australia 2-1. India had begun the series in fourth place, just behind South Africa and Sri Lanka, but South Africa rsquo;s 2-1 series win over eighth-placed West Indies earlier this month relegated them to fourth position and put Sri Lanka second, a fraction of a ratings point ahead of India in third spot.  Following their historic 72-run victory in the third Test in Perth and the drawn match just finished in Adelaide, India moved ahead of Sri Lanka and now sit in second place with 111 ratings points mdash; two ahead of their south Asia rival and three in front of the Proteas.
  Having started the series with 143 ratings points, Australia are still out in front despite losing two ratings points over the course of the series.   TEST RANKINGS  1. Australia (141 ratings points); 2. India (111); 3. Sri Lanka (109); 4. South Africa (108); 5. England (107); 6. Pakistan (94); 7. New Zealand (93); 8. West Indies (73); 9. Bangladesh (2).    
	North beat South   Ahmedabad: North Zone routed South Zone by eight wickets on the Day III of their Duleep Trophy match at Motera. Chasing 70 runs in their second innings, North Zone reached the target in 18.3 overs. Earlier, South Zone were bundled out for 211 in the second innings.   In Rajkot, a defiant 160 by Central Zone skipper Mohammed Kaif could not help his side to take first innings lead over West Zone. They were bundled out at 384, 27 runs short of West Zone rsquo;s 411.  In their second innings, West Zone stretched their overall lead to 125 with both the openers Sahil Kukreja (40) and Ajinkya Rahane (53) unbeaten at the crease.   SUMMARISED SCORES  South Zone 157 and 211. North Zone 299 and 72/2. North Zone won by 8 wickets.  West Zone 411 and 99/0 (S. Kukreja 40 n.o., A. Rahane 53 n.o.). Central Zone 384. Match to continue.    
	NZC, Bond   end contract  Wellington: Fast bowler Shane Bond has had his contract with New Zealand Cricket (NZC) terminated after the player signed for the rebel Twenty20 Indian Cricket League (ICL).  The two parties cancelled the contract by mutual consent, New Zealand Cricket said in a statement Monday, adding that the door had been left open for Bond to represent his country again in the future.    
	 Pak squad  Karachi: Pakistani selectors Monday included four uncapped players in the squad for the fourth ODI against Zimbabwe on Wednesday. The uncapped players are openers, Khurrum Manzoor and Khalid Latif and pacers Sohail Khan and Wahab Riaz.  THE SQUAD mdash; Shoaib Malik (capt), Nasir Jamshed, Khalid Latif, Khurrum Manzoor, Mohammad Yousuf, Younis Khan, Misbah-Ul-Haq, Shahid Afridi, Fawad Alam, Sarfraz Ahmed, Sohail Tanvir, Kamran Hussain, Sohail Khan and Wahab Riaz.
                                                                                                                                                                   
